Changes on Sauerkraut genus level â overall

In the following thereâs one plot and table for each of the 20 most common bacteria genusâ. The genusâ are sorted from most common to least common (based on all our samples).

Code 
# create a dataset with all taxonomic groupings in columns
dat_tax <- tse %>% 
  rowData() %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(species = row.names(.))
row.names(dat_tax) <- NULL

# create a dataset for matching the intervention and participant id variables to the samples
dat_samples <- dat %>% 
  select(participant_id, inter_treat) %>% 
  mutate(sample = row.names(.))
row.names(dat_samples) <- NULL

# create one base dataset for all figures
dat_relAbd <- tse %>% 
  assay("relAbd") %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(species = row.names(.)) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = -species, names_to = "sample", values_to = "relative_abundance") %>% 
  dplyr::left_join(dat_samples, by = "sample") %>% 
  mutate(inter_treat  = factor(inter_treat, levels = c("Baseline.Fresh","After.Fresh","Baseline.Pasteurized",
                                                       "After.Pasteurized","Baseline.FollowUp")),
         treatment    = case_when(grepl("Baseline", inter_treat) ~ "Baseline",
                                  grepl("After",    inter_treat) ~ "After",
                                  TRUE                           ~ NA_character_),
         treatment    = factor(treatment, levels = c("Baseline", "After")),
         intervention = case_when(grepl("Fresh",       inter_treat) ~ "Fresh",
                                  grepl("Pasteurized", inter_treat) ~ "Pasteurized",
                                  grepl("FollowUp",    inter_treat) ~ "FollowUp",
                                  TRUE                              ~ NA_character_),
         intervention = factor(intervention, levels = c("Fresh", "Pasteurized", "FollowUp"))) %>% 
  select(participant_id, inter_treat, treatment, intervention, relative_abundance, species) %>% 
  dplyr::left_join(dat_tax, by = "species")

# summarize per genus
dat_relAbd <- dat_relAbd %>% 
  group_by(participant_id, inter_treat, genus) %>% 
  summarize(treatment          = first(treatment),
            intervention       = first(intervention),
            relative_abundance = sum(relative_abundance, na.rm = TRUE))
Code 
# create a vector of the most common bacteria genus'
genus_vec <- dat_relAbd %>% 
  group_by(genus) %>% 
  summarize(relAbd = sum(relative_abundance, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(relAbd)) %>% 
  slice(1:20) %>% 
  pull(genus) %>% 
  as.character()

# restrict the data to these genus' and remove the follow-up measurements
dat_relAbd_genus <- dat_relAbd %>% 
  filter(genus %in% genus_vec) %>% 
  filter(intervention != "FollowUp")
Code 
# create plots and tables
results_list <- lapply(genus_vec, function(x) {
  if (!(x %in% dat_relAbd_genus$genus))
    return(paste("genus", x, "is not appearing in the data."))
  
  # plot and development table
  generalResults_list <- dat_relAbd_genus %>% 
    filter(genus == x) %>% 
    plot_crossoverBoxplots(y_var            = "relative_abundance",
                           intervention_var = "intervention",
                           t_var            = "treatment",
                           subject_var      = "participant_id",
                           title            = paste("Genus", x),
                           y_isRelAbundance = TRUE)
  
  # add the information how many samples had a relative abundance >= 1%
  tab_1abundance <- dat_relAbd_genus %>% 
    filter(genus == x) %>% 
    group_by(intervention, treatment) %>% 
    summarize(share_atLeast1percent = sum(relative_abundance >= 1) / n()) %>% 
    mutate(share_atLeast1percent = paste0(round(100 * share_atLeast1percent, 1), "%"))
  
  list(ggplot_object  = generalResults_list$ggplot_object,
       results_table  = generalResults_list$results_table,
       tab_1abundance = tab_1abundance)
})
